               <lb/><date calendar="#suhur">twenty, two hundred and one thousand</date> [i.e., 1220], or the year <date calendar="#fasli">1227</date><note>1227 appears to be a Fasli year; however, it does not correspond to the Suhur
                  year 1220 written earlier in the document using terms derived from the Arabic
                  words for numbers. Whereas Shaʿban 1227 converts to June/July 1817 of the
                  Gregorian calendar, Shaʿban 1220 yields a date of May/June 1820. The document
                  also references the Hindu intercalary month Adhik Jyeshta, which is inserted to
                  reconcile lunar and solar modes of reckoning time. Within the period in question,
                  the months Adhik Jyeshta and Shaʿban coincided at the end of the Suhur year 1220;
                  hence, we determine that the document is most accurately dated to May/June
                  1820.</note> 
